## Issue description
I have some problems using the `overload_cast<>` function where code compiles fine using Clang but fails for Gcc/Intel. In this scenario the overload of a template class member function is based on constness.
Even after consulting the documentation, especially [this section](http://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/classes.html#overloaded-methods), I still don't see what the problem might be.

## Minimal Failing Example
The following code compiles using `Clang 6.0.0` but fails for `gcc 5.4.1` and `icpc 17.0.4`. I made sure that the `-std=c++14` is set and also tried to enforce the C++14 features of pybind11 using `PYBIND11_CPP_STANDARD`.
```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

template <typename T>
class TemplateClass {
private:
    T t;

public:
    TemplateClass() : t(1.) {}

    auto&       foo() { return t; }
    const auto& foo() const { return t; }
    auto&       bar(T& a) { return a; }
    const auto& bar(T& a) const { return a; }
};


PYBIND11_MODULE(SomeModule, m) {
    py::class_<TemplateClass<double>>(m, "TemplateClass")
        .def("bar", py::overload_cast<double&>(&TemplateClass<double>::bar))
        .def("foo", py::overload_cast<>(&TemplateClass<double>::foo));
}
```
With `g++` I get the following error:
```
error: no match for call to ‘(const pybind11::detail::overload_cast_impl<double&>) (<unresolved overloaded function type>)’
         .def("bar", py::overload_cast<double&>(&TemplateClass<double>::bar))
```
The `unresolved overloaded function type` portion indicates that the compile does not know which overloaded function to use and indeed the compiler error vanishes when removing one of the overloads for each function. How do I indicate which overload the compiler should use?
Compilation also fails if I try to export the const versions using `py::const_`.

What am I missing here?

